observations.recommendation:
Ensure strict adherence to relevant provisions of COA Circular 97-002 and other pertinent laws, rules and regulations in the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to issue demand letters to the accountable officer who is no longer connected to the Municipality, requiring him to liquidate all long outstanding advances; and

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to withhold payment of salary and other money due to those AOs with unliquidated CAs aged more than one year for the settlement of their outstanding CAs.

Ensure the implementation/enforcement of the programs, projects and activities embodied in the Municipality’s ESWM Plan pursuant to Republic Act 9003, such as:

Segregation at source of solid waste;
"No segregation, no collection" policy;
Creation of Materials Recovery Facility (MRF) in every barangay; and
Development of disposal facility in the Municipality.

Ensure strict adherence to relevant provisions of COA Circular 97-002 and other pertinent laws, rules and regulations in the granting, utilization and liquidation of CAs;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to issue a demand letter for those accountable officers who are no longer connected to the Municipality, requiring them to liquidate all long outstanding advances; and

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to withhold payment of salary and other money due to those AOs with unliquidated CAs aged more than one year for the settlement of their outstanding CAs.

Follow-up and monitor those projects with pending documentary requirements to enable their implementation;

Hasten the reprogramming/realignment of the appropriation for projects with unresolved problems/issues; and

Monitor closely the implementation of planned developmental programs and projects of the 20% DF to ensure the attainment of desirable socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes.

Strictly comply to the provisions of Republic Act 9003 in proper segregation, collection, transport, storage, treatment and disposal of solid waste.

Ensure the implementation/enforcement of the programs, projects and activities embodied in the Municipality’s ESWM Plan pursuant to Republic Act 9003, such as:

Segregation at source of solid waste;

“No segregation, no collection” policy;

Creation of Materials Recovery Facility (MRF) in every barangay; and

Development of disposal facility in the Municipality.

Intensify efforts to timely complete the annual physical count of PPE items and undertake the following steps to account for all existing PPE items in the Municipality:

Require each offices/units of the Municipality to conduct their respective inventory-taking, tagging (inventory stickers) and recording of all PPE items present in the offices and the same shall be validated by the Inspectorate Committee and the Supply Unit;

Turn-over to the Supply Unit all defective or non-functional PPE items for proper recording and disposal;

The Supply Unit shall consolidate all validated inventory reports from the respective offices, together with the respective property numbers for each PPE items, which shall be the basis for preparation of Property Cards and Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);

The Supply Unit shall prepare the necessary Acknowledgement Receipt (ARE), with corresponding serial numbers, to be issued to the concerned accountable officers/property holders, and shall maintain copies of duly received ARE;

The Supply Unit shall furnish the Accounting Unit the electronic and hard copies of the RPCPPE for their reconciliation with the accounting records; and

The Accounting Unit shall determine any discrepancies between the RPCPPE and accounting records and prepare the necessary Subsidiary Ledger to record all unaccounted PPE items.

Afterwards, require the heads of the Accounting Unit and Supply Unit to strictly adhere to existing rules and regulations on the maintenance of PPELC and Property Cards and ensure the conduct of the required annual physical count of PPE and timely reconciliation with the Accounting and Supply records against the related PPELC and Property Cards to facilitate timely verification and adjustment of any discrepancies noted.

We recommended that Management:
Follow-up and monitor those projects with pending documentary requirements to enable their implementation;
Hasten the reprogramming/realignment of the appropriation for projects with unresolved problems/issues; and
Monitor closely the implementation of planned developmental programs and projects of the 20% DF to ensure the attainment of desirable socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes.

Management cited various reasons as to why the said projects were not implemented in CY 2016, such as, but not limited to:
Absence of a surveyor to do the survey and titling of the lot for Public Terminal and Relocation, Parcellary and Road Survey;
Lack of supplier to do the High Definition Images Maps of Nasipit;
Unused appropriation for the Construction of Farm-to-Market Road (Aclan to Hinandayan) due to absence of any damage in the road;
Unclaimed Barangay Development Material Assistance by some barangays due to unliquidated previous assistance; and
Implementation of some programs/projects were suspended due to legal issues.

Further, they stated that the funds appropriated for the two (2) unimplemented projects will be reprogrammed to another project and the assistance for barangay projects will be implemented by the LGU in case the barangays will not be able to liquidate their outstanding claims.

Auditor’s Rejoinder:
We are reiterating our recommendations stated above.
